{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (load them first via ToolSearch with query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\"). Research this angle and return findings with cited URLs.\n\nANGLE: Relative leverage of self-improvement / compounding layers for a small LOCAL LLM build (single 8B model, 16GB RAM, e.g. qwen3:8b via Ollama). The layers in question: (a) skills / experiential memory, (b) routing / model-cascade / navigator (picking which sub-policy or context to use), (c) distillation (fine-tuning a small student on traces). Which gives the most measurable gain per unit of engineering for a local build, and in what order should they be wired? Look for:\n- Evidence on test-time / in-context learning (skills, memory) vs fine-tuning gains for small models.\n- LLM routing / cascade effectiveness and cost-quality tradeoffs.\n- Distillation gains for small (7-8B) student models and the cost of doing it locally.\n- Any \"compound AI systems\" framing (Berkeley AI blog, DSPy) on where leverage lies.\n\nSearch queries to try: \"compound AI systems Berkeley blog\", \"LLM routing cascade cost quality\", \"in-context learning vs fine-tuning small models\", \"distillation 7B student model gains\", \"self-improving agent in-context vs weight update\", \"DSPy optimization vs fine-tuning\".\n\nDo 6-10 searches, fetch 5-7 relevant pages. Extract concrete claims and numbers about relative leverage. Return findings only as your final message, each with claim + source URL + reliability note. Be concrete about ordering recommendation for a local 8B build."},"uuid":"7aa3a7e9-6681-43da-a364-24a2ffb63390","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:01.191Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
