{"parentUuid":"c8967b01-59db-484e-8372-ce0167eb313b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NGJzuTTiN16w8iCSTT1bVm","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"compound AI systems Berkeley blog where leverage lies\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"The Shift from Models to Compound AI Systems – The Berkeley Artificial Intelligence Research Blog\",\"url\":\"https://bair.berkeley.edu/blog/2024/02/18/compound-ai-systems/\"},{\"title\":\"What are Compound AI Systems? | Databricks\",\"url\":\"https://www.databricks.com/blog/what-are-compound-ai-systems\"},{\"title\":\"The evolution of Compound AI systems | by Jason Yip | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@jasonyip_77999/the-evolution-of-compound-ai-systems-77d3f70394eb\"},{\"title\":\"Compound AI systems explained\",\"url\":\"https://www.baseten.co/blog/compound-ai-systems-explained/\"},{\"title\":\"A Guide to Compound AI Systems\",\"url\":\"https://www.bentoml.com/blog/a-guide-to-compound-ai-systems\"},{\"title\":\"Compound AI Systems: The Future of Scalable Intelligence | JD Meier\",\"url\":\"https://jdmeier.com/compound-ai-systems/\"},{\"title\":\"Compound AI Systems: The Future of Specialized Intelligence - Artefact\",\"url\":\"https://www.artefact.com/blog/compound-ai-systems-the-future-of-specialized-intelligence/\"},{\"title\":\"From Standalone LLMs to Integrated Intelligence: A Survey of Compound AI Systems\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.04565v1\"},{\"title\":\"The Evolution of Compound AI Systems | Tredence\",\"url\":\"https://www.tredence.com/blog/the-evolution-of-compound-ai-systems\"},{\"title\":\"Why Compound AI Systems is the Future of Complex Problem-Solving | by Ashish Jaiman | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://ashishjaiman.medium.com/why-a-compound-ai-systems-is-the-future-of-complex-problem-solving-bd7be16ed57f\"}]\n\nI found the Berkeley blog post on compound AI systems. The first search result is directly from the Berkeley Artificial Intelligence Research Blog discussing the shift from models to compound AI systems. \n\nBased on the blog post, state-of-the-art AI results are increasingly obtained by compound systems with multiple components, not just monolithic models. The blog explains that this shift to compound systems opens many interesting design questions, but it is also exciting, because it means leading AI results can be achieved through clever engineering, not just scaling up training.\n\nThe key insight regarding where leverage lies is that some tasks are easier to improve via system design, and while LLMs appear to follow remarkable scaling laws, in many applications, scaling offers lower returns-vs-cost than building a compound system.\n\nThe blog provides concrete examples, such as Google's AlphaCode 2 set state-of-the-art results in programming through a carefully engineered system that uses LLMs to generate up to 1 million possible solutions for a task and then filter down the set.\n\nYou can access the full Berkeley blog post at: https://bair.berkeley.edu/blog/2024/02/18/compound-ai-systems/\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"11c23934-babc-432e-a2e3-2eb481f48fda","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:16.330Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"compound AI systems Berkeley blog where leverage lies","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01KiSQYAoMbPXdWxyDtcHnEX","content":[{"title":"The Shift from Models to Compound AI Systems – The Berkeley Artificial Intelligence Research Blog","url":"https://bair.berkeley.edu/blog/2024/02/18/compound-ai-systems/"},{"title":"What are Compound AI Systems? | Databricks","url":"https://www.databricks.com/blog/what-are-compound-ai-systems"},{"title":"The evolution of Compound AI systems | by Jason Yip | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@jasonyip_77999/the-evolution-of-compound-ai-systems-77d3f70394eb"},{"title":"Compound AI systems explained","url":"https://www.baseten.co/blog/compound-ai-systems-explained/"},{"title":"A Guide to Compound AI Systems","url":"https://www.bentoml.com/blog/a-guide-to-compound-ai-systems"},{"title":"Compound AI Systems: The Future of Scalable Intelligence | JD Meier","url":"https://jdmeier.com/compound-ai-systems/"},{"title":"Compound AI Systems: The Future of Specialized Intelligence - Artefact","url":"https://www.artefact.com/blog/compound-ai-systems-the-future-of-specialized-intelligence/"},{"title":"From Standalone LLMs to Integrated Intelligence: A Survey of Compound AI Systems","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.04565v1"},{"title":"The Evolution of Compound AI Systems | Tredence","url":"https://www.tredence.com/blog/the-evolution-of-compound-ai-systems"},{"title":"Why Compound AI Systems is the Future of Complex Problem-Solving | by Ashish Jaiman | Medium","url":"https://ashishjaiman.medium.com/why-a-compound-ai-systems-is-the-future-of-complex-problem-solving-bd7be16ed57f"}]},"I found the Berkeley blog post on compound AI systems. The first search result is directly from the Berkeley Artificial Intelligence Research Blog discussing the shift from models to compound AI systems. \n\nBased on the blog post, state-of-the-art AI results are increasingly obtained by compound systems with multiple components, not just monolithic models. The blog explains that this shift to compound systems opens many interesting design questions, but it is also exciting, because it means leading AI results can be achieved through clever engineering, not just scaling up training.\n\nThe key insight regarding where leverage lies is that some tasks are easier to improve via system design, and while LLMs appear to follow remarkable scaling laws, in many applications, scaling offers lower returns-vs-cost than building a compound system.\n\nThe blog provides concrete examples, such as Google's AlphaCode 2 set state-of-the-art results in programming through a carefully engineered system that uses LLMs to generate up to 1 million possible solutions for a task and then filter down the set.\n\nYou can access the full Berkeley blog post at: https://bair.berkeley.edu/blog/2024/02/18/compound-ai-systems/"],"durationSeconds":7.212095082999207,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c8967b01-59db-484e-8372-ce0167eb313b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b9b73ee5-c562-41b1-a8da-df8f810a1fcd","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UEvogaxM8S1BJsEWUgpANn","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"in-context learning vs fine-tuning small models gains comparison\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Few-shot Fine-tuning vs. In-context Learning: A Fair Comparison and Evaluation - ACL Anthology\",\"url\":\"https://aclanthology.org/2023.findings-acl.779/\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning vs In-Context Learning: Which Strategy Makes AI Models More Useful? - Neural DeepLearn Academy\",\"url\":\"https://padhai.onefourthlabs.in/fine-tuning-vs-in-context-learning-ai-models/\"},{\"title\":\"In-Context Learning vs Fine‑Tuning: Which Faster? | newline\",\"url\":\"https://www.newline.co/@Dipen/in-context-learning-vs-finetuning-which-faster--d865b4ad\"},{\"title\":\"[2305.16938] Few-shot Fine-tuning vs. In-context Learning: A Fair Comparison and Evaluation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.16938\"},{\"title\":\"On the generalization of language models from in-context learning and finetuning: a controlled study\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.00661v1\"},{\"title\":\"Deeper Insights Without Updates: The Power of In-Context Learning Over Fine-Tuning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.04691v1\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-tuning vs. in-context learning: New research guides better LLM customization for real-world tasks | VentureBeat\",\"url\":\"https://venturebeat.com/ai/fine-tuning-vs-in-context-learning-new-research-guides-better-llm-customization-for-real-world-tasks\"},{\"title\":\"Why is in-context learning lower quality than fine-tuning? And…what if it wasn't?\",\"url\":\"https://hazyresearch.stanford.edu/blog/2023-06-12-icl-vs-finetuning\"},{\"title\":\"Few-shot Fine-tuning vs. In-context Learning: A Fair Comparison and   Evaluation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2305.16938\"},{\"title\":\"Evaluating Generalization and Representation Stability in Small LMs via Prompting, Fine-Tuning and Out-of-Distribution Prompts\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.17289\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's a comprehensive comparison of in-context learning (ICL) vs fine-tuning for small models:\n\n## Performance Gains\n\nThe comparison shows mixed but nuanced results:\n\nBoth approaches generalize similarly, exhibiting large variation depending on properties such as model size and the number of examples. However, model size is critical—small models are not efficient in-context learners, meaning for a smaller Flash-8B model, in-context learning performs worse than vanilla fine-tuning on some tasks.\n\nWhen using augmented datasets, the picture improves for fine-tuning: When models were fine-tuned on augmented datasets, the gains were significant, with augmented fine-tuning significantly improving generalization and outperforming both standard fine-tuning and plain ICL.\n\n## Recent Findings on Small Models\n\nRecent research suggests the smallest model variants, despite having limited in-context learning ability, achieve substantial accuracy increases through fine-tuning, suggesting that even low-capacity models retain latent flexibility when supervised adaptation is allowed.\n\n## Trade-offs\n\nIn-context learning incurs costs per query scaling with token count, where a prompt with 50 examples might cost 3–5x more than a standard query, while fine-tuning, though requiring upfront investment, reduces per-use costs once trained.\n\nThe practical takeaway: while prompting offers convenience, fine-tuning remains the dominant approach in small-data regimes, particularly when performance is critical and modest training is feasible.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"9ec266fe-e396-4bbf-bb1d-0e6b54fb0155","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:18.445Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"in-context learning vs fine-tuning small models gains comparison","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_012K5kKhDpwcj7ssnwcaXEJ5","content":[{"title":"Few-shot Fine-tuning vs. In-context Learning: A Fair Comparison and Evaluation - ACL Anthology","url":"https://aclanthology.org/2023.findings-acl.779/"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning vs In-Context Learning: Which Strategy Makes AI Models More Useful? - Neural DeepLearn Academy","url":"https://padhai.onefourthlabs.in/fine-tuning-vs-in-context-learning-ai-models/"},{"title":"In-Context Learning vs Fine‑Tuning: Which Faster? | newline","url":"https://www.newline.co/@Dipen/in-context-learning-vs-finetuning-which-faster--d865b4ad"},{"title":"[2305.16938] Few-shot Fine-tuning vs. In-context Learning: A Fair Comparison and Evaluation","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.16938"},{"title":"On the generalization of language models from in-context learning and finetuning: a controlled study","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.00661v1"},{"title":"Deeper Insights Without Updates: The Power of In-Context Learning Over Fine-Tuning","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.04691v1"},{"title":"Fine-tuning vs. in-context learning: New research guides better LLM customization for real-world tasks | VentureBeat","url":"https://venturebeat.com/ai/fine-tuning-vs-in-context-learning-new-research-guides-better-llm-customization-for-real-world-tasks"},{"title":"Why is in-context learning lower quality than fine-tuning? And…what if it wasn't?","url":"https://hazyresearch.stanford.edu/blog/2023-06-12-icl-vs-finetuning"},{"title":"Few-shot Fine-tuning vs. In-context Learning: A Fair Comparison and   Evaluation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2305.16938"},{"title":"Evaluating Generalization and Representation Stability in Small LMs via Prompting, Fine-Tuning and Out-of-Distribution Prompts","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.17289"}]},"Based on the search results, here's a comprehensive comparison of in-context learning (ICL) vs fine-tuning for small models:\n\n## Performance Gains\n\nThe comparison shows mixed but nuanced results:\n\nBoth approaches generalize similarly, exhibiting large variation depending on properties such as model size and the number of examples. However, model size is critical—small models are not efficient in-context learners, meaning for a smaller Flash-8B model, in-context learning performs worse than vanilla fine-tuning on some tasks.\n\nWhen using augmented datasets, the picture improves for fine-tuning: When models were fine-tuned on augmented datasets, the gains were significant, with augmented fine-tuning significantly improving generalization and outperforming both standard fine-tuning and plain ICL.\n\n## Recent Findings on Small Models\n\nRecent research suggests the smallest model variants, despite having limited in-context learning ability, achieve substantial accuracy increases through fine-tuning, suggesting that even low-capacity models retain latent flexibility when supervised adaptation is allowed.\n\n## Trade-offs\n\nIn-context learning incurs costs per query scaling with token count, where a prompt with 50 examples might cost 3–5x more than a standard query, while fine-tuning, though requiring upfront investment, reduces per-use costs once trained.\n\nThe practical takeaway: while prompting offers convenience, fine-tuning remains the dominant approach in small-data regimes, particularly when performance is critical and modest training is feasible."],"durationSeconds":8.818967000000178,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b9b73ee5-c562-41b1-a8da-df8f810a1fcd","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
