{"parentUuid":"702ec45e-cec8-46ff-a54c-dd59aef0295e","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01GTmLVG4fcuiwtHbquWWpLy","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01FXZXR89gZyPAcxCk6TLToC","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://bair.berkeley.edu/blog/2024/02/18/compound-ai-systems/","prompt":"Extract concrete claims about where leverage lies in compound AI systems vs scaling/training a single model. Any specific numbers, examples (AlphaCode, retrieval, ensembling), and the argument that system design beats model scaling for returns per cost. Also note any mention of small/local models."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2597,"cache_read_input_tokens":15998,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2597,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqMjM6hFxzBsxrBPgNt","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"6a20a6d9-66b9-438b-93d9-89ce53511efd","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:34.371Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"6a20a6d9-66b9-438b-93d9-89ce53511efd","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01GTmLVG4fcuiwtHbquWWpLy","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01DLkSG48WpTfkrehcvm9chj","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"DSPy optimization vs fine-tuning prompt optimization gains accuracy"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2597,"cache_read_input_tokens":15998,"output_tokens":289,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2597},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":289,"cache_read_input_tokens":15998,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2597,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2597,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqMjM6hFxzBsxrBPgNt","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"8fe4a147-837d-4afc-b66e-dde7ab09ec64","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:34.600Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"6a20a6d9-66b9-438b-93d9-89ce53511efd","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FXZXR89gZyPAcxCk6TLToC","type":"tool_result","content":"# Leverage in Compound AI Systems vs. Model Scaling\n\n## Core Argument: System Design Over Scaling\n\nThe paper contends that engineering system designs often provides better returns-on-investment than scaling individual models. The authors illustrate this with coding contests: \"suppose that the current best LLM can solve coding contest problems 30% of the time, and tripling its training budget would increase this to 35%\" while \"engineering a system that samples from the model multiple times, tests each sample, etc. might increase performance to 80%.\"\n\n## Concrete Examples\n\n**AlphaCode 2**: Generates up to 1 million candidate solutions, then filters them down—achieving 85th percentile performance on competitive programming without larger model scaling.\n\n**Medprompt**: Uses GPT-4 with retrieval-augmented few-shot prompting and ensembling (up to 11 samples). This approach \"outperforms specialized medical models\" through orchestration rather than model size.\n\n**Gemini's CoT@32**: Samples the model 32 times with chain-of-thought reasoning, reaching 90.04% on MMLU versus GPT-4's 86.4%.\n\n## Key Leverage Points\n\n- **Multiple model calls + filtering** (AlphaCode's approach)\n- **Retrieval + ensemble voting** (Medprompt's strategy)\n- **Routing to smaller, cheaper models** where appropriate (mentioned regarding GitHub Copilot's smaller model choices)\n\nThe paper emphasizes that \"iterating on a system design is often much faster than waiting for training runs,\" positioning compound systems as the practical path forward."}]},"uuid":"692d466e-3382-4fdf-9c86-e97380cc4a82","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:42.032Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":31639,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Leverage in Compound AI Systems vs. Model Scaling\n\n## Core Argument: System Design Over Scaling\n\nThe paper contends that engineering system designs often provides better returns-on-investment than scaling individual models. The authors illustrate this with coding contests: \"suppose that the current best LLM can solve coding contest problems 30% of the time, and tripling its training budget would increase this to 35%\" while \"engineering a system that samples from the model multiple times, tests each sample, etc. might increase performance to 80%.\"\n\n## Concrete Examples\n\n**AlphaCode 2**: Generates up to 1 million candidate solutions, then filters them down—achieving 85th percentile performance on competitive programming without larger model scaling.\n\n**Medprompt**: Uses GPT-4 with retrieval-augmented few-shot prompting and ensembling (up to 11 samples). This approach \"outperforms specialized medical models\" through orchestration rather than model size.\n\n**Gemini's CoT@32**: Samples the model 32 times with chain-of-thought reasoning, reaching 90.04% on MMLU versus GPT-4's 86.4%.\n\n## Key Leverage Points\n\n- **Multiple model calls + filtering** (AlphaCode's approach)\n- **Retrieval + ensemble voting** (Medprompt's strategy)\n- **Routing to smaller, cheaper models** where appropriate (mentioned regarding GitHub Copilot's smaller model choices)\n\nThe paper emphasizes that \"iterating on a system design is often much faster than waiting for training runs,\" positioning compound systems as the practical path forward.","durationMs":7470,"url":"https://bair.berkeley.edu/blog/2024/02/18/compound-ai-systems/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"6a20a6d9-66b9-438b-93d9-89ce53511efd","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"8fe4a147-837d-4afc-b66e-dde7ab09ec64","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DLkSG48WpTfkrehcvm9chj","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"DSPy optimization vs fine-tuning prompt optimization gains accuracy\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"A Comparative Study of DSPy Teleprompter Algorithms for Aligning Large Language Models Evaluation Metrics to Human Evaluation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2412.15298v1\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning and Prompt Optimization: Two Great Steps that Work Better Together\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2407.10930v1\"},{\"title\":\"Understanding Optimizers in DSPy. Optimizers with the right metrics… | by Jules S. Damji | The Modern Scientist | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/the-modern-scientist/understanding-optimizers-in-dspy-1ea9451c128b\"},{\"title\":\"Pipelines & Prompt Optimization with DSPy\",\"url\":\"https://www.dbreunig.com/2024/12/12/pipelines-prompt-optimization-with-dspy.html\"},{\"title\":\"DSPy vs prompt engineering: Systematic vs manual tuning\",\"url\":\"https://www.statsig.com/perspectives/dspy-vs-prompt-tuning\"},{\"title\":\"Prompt Optimization as a State-Space Search Problem\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.18619\"},{\"title\":\"DSPy compilers: Automatic prompt optimization\",\"url\":\"https://www.statsig.com/perspectives/dspy-compilers-prompt-optimization\"},{\"title\":\"UMB@PerAnsSumm 2025: Enhancing Perspective-Aware Summarization with Prompt Optimization and Supervised Fine-Tuning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.11118\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what the research shows about DSPy optimization versus fine-tuning and prompt optimization gains:\n\n## Key Differences\n\nDSPy focuses on optimizing prompts and pipeline configurations through declarative modules and automated teleprompters without modifying the pre-trained LLM's weights. Because the weight parameters of the model are not tuned, this approach is relatively faster and cost-effective as it requires less computational resources.\n\nIn contrast, fine-tuning involves updating the LLM's weights using task-specific training data and may yield more robust performance for narrowly defined applications but is usually computationally more intensive.\n\n## Accuracy Gains\n\nResearch comparing these approaches shows significant potential improvements. Simple approaches for optimizing the prompts and weights together outperform directly optimizing weights alone and prompts alone by up to 65% and 5%, respectively, on average across language models in multi-hop QA, mathematical reasoning, and feature-based classification tasks.\n\n## Practical Recommendations\n\nInstruction optimization with MIPROv2 tunes instructions and examples together and shows measurable lift on setups like HotpotQA, and is the quick path to squeeze more accuracy out of an existing program. A recommended approach is to start with automatic few-shot, add MIPROv2 when formats wobble, then fine-tune only if traffic or drift demands it, keeping costs sane while compounding gains.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"da5857ef-9734-4acd-b614-6731df9a2c8b","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:42.880Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"DSPy optimization vs fine-tuning prompt optimization gains accuracy","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_012v75WQ2qN16rx2ov9ZYAbe","content":[{"title":"A Comparative Study of DSPy Teleprompter Algorithms for Aligning Large Language Models Evaluation Metrics to Human Evaluation","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2412.15298v1"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning and Prompt Optimization: Two Great Steps that Work Better Together","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2407.10930v1"},{"title":"Understanding Optimizers in DSPy. Optimizers with the right metrics… | by Jules S. Damji | The Modern Scientist | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/the-modern-scientist/understanding-optimizers-in-dspy-1ea9451c128b"},{"title":"Pipelines & Prompt Optimization with DSPy","url":"https://www.dbreunig.com/2024/12/12/pipelines-prompt-optimization-with-dspy.html"},{"title":"DSPy vs prompt engineering: Systematic vs manual tuning","url":"https://www.statsig.com/perspectives/dspy-vs-prompt-tuning"},{"title":"Prompt Optimization as a State-Space Search Problem","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.18619"},{"title":"DSPy compilers: Automatic prompt optimization","url":"https://www.statsig.com/perspectives/dspy-compilers-prompt-optimization"},{"title":"UMB@PerAnsSumm 2025: Enhancing Perspective-Aware Summarization with Prompt Optimization and Supervised Fine-Tuning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.11118"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what the research shows about DSPy optimization versus fine-tuning and prompt optimization gains:\n\n## Key Differences\n\nDSPy focuses on optimizing prompts and pipeline configurations through declarative modules and automated teleprompters without modifying the pre-trained LLM's weights. Because the weight parameters of the model are not tuned, this approach is relatively faster and cost-effective as it requires less computational resources.\n\nIn contrast, fine-tuning involves updating the LLM's weights using task-specific training data and may yield more robust performance for narrowly defined applications but is usually computationally more intensive.\n\n## Accuracy Gains\n\nResearch comparing these approaches shows significant potential improvements. Simple approaches for optimizing the prompts and weights together outperform directly optimizing weights alone and prompts alone by up to 65% and 5%, respectively, on average across language models in multi-hop QA, mathematical reasoning, and feature-based classification tasks.\n\n## Practical Recommendations\n\nInstruction optimization with MIPROv2 tunes instructions and examples together and shows measurable lift on setups like HotpotQA, and is the quick path to squeeze more accuracy out of an existing program. A recommended approach is to start with automatic few-shot, add MIPROv2 when formats wobble, then fine-tune only if traffic or drift demands it, keeping costs sane while compounding gains."],"durationSeconds":7.909802458000369,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"8fe4a147-837d-4afc-b66e-dde7ab09ec64","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"da5857ef-9734-4acd-b614-6731df9a2c8b","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01R75U8pMRtTg6TnBRBFzX3w","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me fetch a few more sources for concrete numbers on the \"fine-tuning + prompt optimization together\" finding, the routing tradeoffs, and the in-context vs fine-tuning controlled study."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1981,"cache_read_input_tokens":18595,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1981,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqNghdwmBCUJg8duhzH","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"e0de93d5-439b-4c17-b823-a84849ac1cd8","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:45.898Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"e0de93d5-439b-4c17-b823-a84849ac1cd8","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01R75U8pMRtTg6TnBRBFzX3w","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01LoWYvSG8uDgkPD2Sb1fGKw","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2407.10930v1","prompt":"Extract concrete numbers on how prompt optimization vs fine-tuning vs both-together compare. What are the relative gains? Which order should they be done in? Any findings specific to smaller models?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1981,"cache_read_input_tokens":18595,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1981,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqNghdwmBCUJg8duhzH","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"800da38f-0920-47d3-a17c-0661cd1ac9f8","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:47.377Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"800da38f-0920-47d3-a17c-0661cd1ac9f8","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01R75U8pMRtTg6TnBRBFzX3w","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Cmc649YhVABQSTYgjKunTR","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"self-improving agent in-context memory vs weight update Voyager Reflexion test-time learning"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1981,"cache_read_input_tokens":18595,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1981,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqNghdwmBCUJg8duhzH","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"e8c21ce0-7fad-4aa0-a662-662e2ded1849","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:48.426Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"800da38f-0920-47d3-a17c-0661cd1ac9f8","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LoWYvSG8uDgkPD2Sb1fGKw","type":"tool_result","content":"# Fine-Tuning vs. Prompt Optimization: Key Findings\n\n## Performance Comparisons\n\nThe research reveals substantial improvements when combining both approaches:\n\n- **HotPotQA**: Combined strategies achieved 5–78% gains over prompt-only approaches and up to 65% gains versus weight-only optimization\n- **GSM8K**: 2.5–10% improvements from tandem strategies\n- **Iris**: -5.9–136% range, showing high variability on this smaller dataset\n\n## Optimal Ordering\n\nThe study tested eight different combinations. Results show **no single clear winner** among three best-performing strategies:\n\n1. Prompt → Fine-tune → Prompt\n2. Fine-tune → Prompt  \n3. Prompt → Prompt\n\nNotably, \"prompt-then-weights-then-prompt\" achieved best results on HotPotQA (37.6% for Mistral) and competitive scores elsewhere.\n\n## Smaller Model Findings\n\nLlama-2-7B and Llama-3-8B showed similar patterns to Mistral-7B. The paper notes that \"optimizing prompts and weights together leads to strong gains over the best setting that only optimizes one of the two\" across all tested models, suggesting the approach generalizes across different model sizes in the 7-8B parameter range.\n\n## Key Insight\n\nThe authors hypothesize that \"prompt optimization before fine-tuning can lead to more successful datapoints\" while \"prompt optimization after fine-tuning can make adjustments to behavior that lead to higher quality.\""}]},"uuid":"2dbb1ce0-82d0-43c1-bf3b-1e3ca194593e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:54.617Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":347215,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Fine-Tuning vs. Prompt Optimization: Key Findings\n\n## Performance Comparisons\n\nThe research reveals substantial improvements when combining both approaches:\n\n- **HotPotQA**: Combined strategies achieved 5–78% gains over prompt-only approaches and up to 65% gains versus weight-only optimization\n- **GSM8K**: 2.5–10% improvements from tandem strategies\n- **Iris**: -5.9–136% range, showing high variability on this smaller dataset\n\n## Optimal Ordering\n\nThe study tested eight different combinations. Results show **no single clear winner** among three best-performing strategies:\n\n1. Prompt → Fine-tune → Prompt\n2. Fine-tune → Prompt  \n3. Prompt → Prompt\n\nNotably, \"prompt-then-weights-then-prompt\" achieved best results on HotPotQA (37.6% for Mistral) and competitive scores elsewhere.\n\n## Smaller Model Findings\n\nLlama-2-7B and Llama-3-8B showed similar patterns to Mistral-7B. The paper notes that \"optimizing prompts and weights together leads to strong gains over the best setting that only optimizes one of the two\" across all tested models, suggesting the approach generalizes across different model sizes in the 7-8B parameter range.\n\n## Key Insight\n\nThe authors hypothesize that \"prompt optimization before fine-tuning can lead to more successful datapoints\" while \"prompt optimization after fine-tuning can make adjustments to behavior that lead to higher quality.\"","durationMs":7022,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2407.10930v1"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"800da38f-0920-47d3-a17c-0661cd1ac9f8","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"e8c21ce0-7fad-4aa0-a662-662e2ded1849","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Cmc649YhVABQSTYgjKunTR","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"self-improving agent in-context memory vs weight update Voyager Reflexion test-time learning\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"EvoTest: Evolutionary Test-Time Learning for Self-Improving Agentic Systems\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.13220\"},{\"title\":\"EvoTest: Evolutionary Test-Time Learning for Self-Improving Agentic Systems\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.13220\"},{\"title\":\"In-Memory Learning: A Declarative Learning Framework for Large Language   Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2403.02757\"},{\"title\":\"Contextual Agentic Memory is a Memo, Not True Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2604.27707\"},{\"title\":\"Implementing — Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@vikram40441/implementing-reflexion-language-agents-with-verbal-reinforcement-learning-e4cb300278b6\"},{\"title\":\"1. Introduction\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.04466\"},{\"title\":\"Decocted Experience Improves Test-Time Inference in LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.04373\"},{\"title\":\"Scaling Self-Evolving Agents via Parametric Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2606.04536v1\"},{\"title\":\"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.07952\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding self-improving agents, in-context memory vs. weight updates, and test-time learning:\n\n## Key Distinction: In-Context Memory vs. Weight Updates\n\nA prominent line of work enables agents to learn from past mistakes without updating weights. Reflexion allows an agent to verbally reflect on trajectory failures and append these reflections to its prompt for subsequent episodes.\n\n## In-Context Learning Approaches\n\nReflexion agents reflect verbally on task feedback signals and maintain reflective text in an episodic memory buffer. This process induces better decision-making in subsequent trials by providing concrete directions for improvement.\n\nThe common practice for agents based on retrievers is acquiring related experiences and integrating them into the context, which essentially is in-context learning.\n\n## Voyager and Memory Systems\n\nSimilar to Voyager, agents should operate within a stable environment over a long period. Voyager accumulates skills as code in a vector database.\n\n## Limitations of In-Context Memory\n\nA recent critical perspective argues that biological intelligence solved this problem by pairing fast hippocampal exemplar storage with slow neocortical weight consolidation, and current AI agents implement only the first half. Retrieval generalizes by similarity to stored cases; weight-based memory generalizes by applying abstract rules to inputs the agent has never encountered.\n\n## Test-Time Learning Advances\n\nAn emerging research direction studies how agents self-improve from prior interaction experience, either at test time or through weight updates during training. ExpeL collects trajectories on training tasks, abstracts them into insights, and retrieves both insights and successful past experiences at test time.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"59b831bc-b404-4a97-b6d9-6159b8182ffd","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:57.217Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"self-improving agent in-context memory vs weight update Voyager Reflexion test-time learning","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01PswWjoy7FCkkCQeJqkFqdS","content":[{"title":"EvoTest: Evolutionary Test-Time Learning for Self-Improving Agentic Systems","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.13220"},{"title":"EvoTest: Evolutionary Test-Time Learning for Self-Improving Agentic Systems","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.13220"},{"title":"In-Memory Learning: A Declarative Learning Framework for Large Language   Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2403.02757"},{"title":"Contextual Agentic Memory is a Memo, Not True Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2604.27707"},{"title":"Implementing — Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning","url":"https://medium.com/@vikram40441/implementing-reflexion-language-agents-with-verbal-reinforcement-learning-e4cb300278b6"},{"title":"1. Introduction","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.04466"},{"title":"Decocted Experience Improves Test-Time Inference in LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.04373"},{"title":"Scaling Self-Evolving Agents via Parametric Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2606.04536v1"},{"title":"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.07952"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding self-improving agents, in-context memory vs. weight updates, and test-time learning:\n\n## Key Distinction: In-Context Memory vs. Weight Updates\n\nA prominent line of work enables agents to learn from past mistakes without updating weights. Reflexion allows an agent to verbally reflect on trajectory failures and append these reflections to its prompt for subsequent episodes.\n\n## In-Context Learning Approaches\n\nReflexion agents reflect verbally on task feedback signals and maintain reflective text in an episodic memory buffer. This process induces better decision-making in subsequent trials by providing concrete directions for improvement.\n\nThe common practice for agents based on retrievers is acquiring related experiences and integrating them into the context, which essentially is in-context learning.\n\n## Voyager and Memory Systems\n\nSimilar to Voyager, agents should operate within a stable environment over a long period. Voyager accumulates skills as code in a vector database.\n\n## Limitations of In-Context Memory\n\nA recent critical perspective argues that biological intelligence solved this problem by pairing fast hippocampal exemplar storage with slow neocortical weight consolidation, and current AI agents implement only the first half. Retrieval generalizes by similarity to stored cases; weight-based memory generalizes by applying abstract rules to inputs the agent has never encountered.\n\n## Test-Time Learning Advances\n\nAn emerging research direction studies how agents self-improve from prior interaction experience, either at test time or through weight updates during training. ExpeL collects trajectories on training tasks, abstracts them into insights, and retrieves both insights and successful past experiences at test time."],"durationSeconds":8.563871875000187,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"e8c21ce0-7fad-4aa0-a662-662e2ded1849","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
