{"parentUuid":"9e9cf664-882a-442d-b022-2bec18e2ba38","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01G9HFt1P1SALthZw2czvzQ8","type":"tool_result","content":"# Few-shot Fine-tuning vs In-context Learning: Key Findings\n\nBased on the abstract provided, the paper's main findings are:\n\n**Overall Comparison:**\nThe researchers found that \"both approaches generalize similarly; they exhibit large variation\" with performance depending heavily on experimental factors rather than the technique itself.\n\n**Key Variables:**\nPerformance varied significantly based on:\n- Model size (tested 125M to 30B parameters)\n- Number of few-shot examples provided\n\n**Main Conclusion:**\nContrary to previous assumptions, \"fine-tuned language models can in fact generalize well out-of-domain.\" The paper challenges the narrative that fine-tuning inherently performs worse than in-context learning.\n\n**Important Context:**\nThe abstract notes that \"robust task adaptation remains a challenge\" for both approaches, suggesting neither method is decisively superior across all conditions.\n\n**Limitation:**\nThe provided content is only the abstract and metadata. Specific quantitative comparisons (exact performance differences, cost metrics, optimal example counts for different model sizes) are not detailed in this excerpt. You would need to consult the full PDF for:\n- Numerical performance deltas\n- Computational cost analyses\n- Size-specific recommendations\n- Detailed challenge dataset results"}]},"uuid":"358ce6c3-d94c-473a-b24b-0cc917021558","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:08.261Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":39922,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Few-shot Fine-tuning vs In-context Learning: Key Findings\n\nBased on the abstract provided, the paper's main findings are:\n\n**Overall Comparison:**\nThe researchers found that \"both approaches generalize similarly; they exhibit large variation\" with performance depending heavily on experimental factors rather than the technique itself.\n\n**Key Variables:**\nPerformance varied significantly based on:\n- Model size (tested 125M to 30B parameters)\n- Number of few-shot examples provided\n\n**Main Conclusion:**\nContrary to previous assumptions, \"fine-tuned language models can in fact generalize well out-of-domain.\" The paper challenges the narrative that fine-tuning inherently performs worse than in-context learning.\n\n**Important Context:**\nThe abstract notes that \"robust task adaptation remains a challenge\" for both approaches, suggesting neither method is decisively superior across all conditions.\n\n**Limitation:**\nThe provided content is only the abstract and metadata. Specific quantitative comparisons (exact performance differences, cost metrics, optimal example counts for different model sizes) are not detailed in this excerpt. You would need to consult the full PDF for:\n- Numerical performance deltas\n- Computational cost analyses\n- Size-specific recommendations\n- Detailed challenge dataset results","durationMs":5007,"url":"https://aclanthology.org/2023.findings-acl.779/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9e9cf664-882a-442d-b022-2bec18e2ba38","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"358ce6c3-d94c-473a-b24b-0cc917021558","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01HJGB3VhiVELvvArQJs3dYb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me get the Dynamic Cheatsheet numbers from the abstract page and the routing/cascade blog with concrete figures."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1234,"cache_read_input_tokens":22905,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1234,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqQYquyujRP81unB9B9","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"d3267bd0-a115-4840-aba8-dec7f63a6834","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:10.853Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"d3267bd0-a115-4840-aba8-dec7f63a6834","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01HJGB3VhiVELvvArQJs3dYb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01MNLKjQPXx78whg2bVX2pPp","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"\"Dynamic Cheatsheet\" test-time learning adaptive memory accuracy improvement results"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1234,"cache_read_input_tokens":22905,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1234,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqQYquyujRP81unB9B9","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"a589ce0b-2c72-4859-99bd-5b80e84ef416","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:11.335Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"a589ce0b-2c72-4859-99bd-5b80e84ef416","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01HJGB3VhiVELvvArQJs3dYb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01MJ49AJNmkdz1fsU5eNbDTi","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://tianpan.co/blog/2025-11-03-llm-routing-model-cascades","prompt":"Extract concrete numbers on cost savings and quality retention from LLM routing and cascades. What percent of queries can be routed to cheap/small models while retaining what percent of frontier quality? Any FrugalGPT or RouteLLM specific figures? Engineering effort notes?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1234,"cache_read_input_tokens":22905,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1234,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqQYquyujRP81unB9B9","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"f2f01279-aa85-496f-9f33-75ff100aae93","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:13.767Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"f2f01279-aa85-496f-9f33-75ff100aae93","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MJ49AJNmkdz1fsU5eNbDTi","type":"tool_result","content":"# LLM Routing Cost Savings: Key Figures\n\n## Cost Reduction Metrics\n\nThe article cites RouteLLM research showing that \"with proper routing, you can maintain 95% of frontier model quality while routing 85% of queries to cheaper models, achieving cost reductions of 45–85% depending on your workload.\"\n\n## Pricing Differentials\n\nCurrent frontier models (Claude Opus) cost approximately $5 per million input tokens and $25 per output million tokens, while efficient models cost $1 and $5 respectively—yielding a 5x cost ratio across the model family.\n\n## Engineering Implementation Order\n\nThe article recommends a phased approach:\n\n1. **Semantic caching first** (simplest ROI, uses existing tools)\n2. **Intent routing** for well-defined categories\n3. **Confidence cascading** for ambiguous queries\n4. **Fallback chains** for reliability\n\n## Early Abstention Benefits\n\nOne technique achieved \"a 13% reduction in cost and 5% reduction in error rate by accepting a 4.1% increase in abstention rate\"—meaning the model explicitly signals uncertainty rather than generating unreliable answers.\n\n## Key Tooling\n\nProduction-ready frameworks mentioned include LiteLLM, RouteLLM, and vLLM's semantic router—reducing custom development needs.\n\nThe article emphasizes that observability and empirically-calibrated thresholds are non-negotiable for production success."}]},"uuid":"2964febd-01b8-4570-9181-0beafc232803","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:20.011Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":53146,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# LLM Routing Cost Savings: Key Figures\n\n## Cost Reduction Metrics\n\nThe article cites RouteLLM research showing that \"with proper routing, you can maintain 95% of frontier model quality while routing 85% of queries to cheaper models, achieving cost reductions of 45–85% depending on your workload.\"\n\n## Pricing Differentials\n\nCurrent frontier models (Claude Opus) cost approximately $5 per million input tokens and $25 per output million tokens, while efficient models cost $1 and $5 respectively—yielding a 5x cost ratio across the model family.\n\n## Engineering Implementation Order\n\nThe article recommends a phased approach:\n\n1. **Semantic caching first** (simplest ROI, uses existing tools)\n2. **Intent routing** for well-defined categories\n3. **Confidence cascading** for ambiguous queries\n4. **Fallback chains** for reliability\n\n## Early Abstention Benefits\n\nOne technique achieved \"a 13% reduction in cost and 5% reduction in error rate by accepting a 4.1% increase in abstention rate\"—meaning the model explicitly signals uncertainty rather than generating unreliable answers.\n\n## Key Tooling\n\nProduction-ready frameworks mentioned include LiteLLM, RouteLLM, and vLLM's semantic router—reducing custom development needs.\n\nThe article emphasizes that observability and empirically-calibrated thresholds are non-negotiable for production success.","durationMs":6062,"url":"https://tianpan.co/blog/2025-11-03-llm-routing-model-cascades"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"f2f01279-aa85-496f-9f33-75ff100aae93","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"a589ce0b-2c72-4859-99bd-5b80e84ef416","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MNLKjQPXx78whg2bVX2pPp","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"\"Dynamic Cheatsheet\" test-time learning adaptive memory accuracy improvement results\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Dynamic Cheatsheet (DC) Framework\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/dynamic-cheatsheet-dc\"},{\"title\":\"[2504.07952] Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.07952\"},{\"title\":\"Paper page - Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/papers/2504.07952\"},{\"title\":\"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.07952\"},{\"title\":\"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory - ACL Anthology\",\"url\":\"https://aclanthology.org/2026.eacl-long.333/\"},{\"title\":\"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/papers/2504.07952\"},{\"title\":\"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory - Paper Detail\",\"url\":\"https://deeplearn.org/arxiv/594856/dynamic-cheatsheet:-test-time-learning-with-adaptive-memory\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/390671520_Dynamic_Cheatsheet_Test-Time_Learning_with_Adaptive_Memory\"},{\"title\":\"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.07952v1\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Dynamic Cheatsheet and its accuracy improvement results:\n\n## Overview\n\nDynamic Cheatsheet is a lightweight framework that equips language models with persistent, adaptive memory for test-time learning by curating problem-solving strategies. The framework uses a dual-module system—with Generator and Curator modules—and integrates retrieval synthesis to efficiently update its external memory during inference.\n\n## Key Accuracy Improvement Results\n\nThe research demonstrates significant improvements across multiple task categories:\n\n**Math and Reasoning Tasks:**\n- Claude 3.5 Sonnet's accuracy more than doubled on AIME math exams once it began retaining algebraic insights across questions.\n- GPT-4o's success rate on the Game of 24 puzzle increased from about 10% to 99% after the model discovered and reused a Python-based solution.\n- Claude 3.5 Sonnet's accuracy more than doubles in Math Equation Solver, reaching 98%.\n\n**Arithmetic Tasks:**\n- In tasks prone to arithmetic mistakes, such as balancing equations, DC enabled GPT-40 and Claude to reach near-perfect accuracy by recalling previously validated code, whereas their baselines stagnated around 50%.\n\n**Knowledge-Demanding Tasks:**\n- Claude achieved a 9% improvement in GPQA-Diamond and an 8% boost on MMLU-Pro Engineering and Physics problems.\n\n## Key Advantages\n\nDC significantly boosts accuracy on arithmetic, reasoning, and code tasks by enabling cumulative learning without modifying model parameters.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"e657d1a3-4628-45db-bc7f-b0e21a54bbad","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:22.800Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"\"Dynamic Cheatsheet\" test-time learning adaptive memory accuracy improvement results","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01KjecaC1LWDFkwF3W3eNmcH","content":[{"title":"Dynamic Cheatsheet (DC) Framework","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/dynamic-cheatsheet-dc"},{"title":"[2504.07952] Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.07952"},{"title":"Paper page - Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory","url":"https://huggingface.co/papers/2504.07952"},{"title":"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.07952"},{"title":"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory - ACL Anthology","url":"https://aclanthology.org/2026.eacl-long.333/"},{"title":"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/papers/2504.07952"},{"title":"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory - Paper Detail","url":"https://deeplearn.org/arxiv/594856/dynamic-cheatsheet:-test-time-learning-with-adaptive-memory"},{"title":"(PDF) Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/390671520_Dynamic_Cheatsheet_Test-Time_Learning_with_Adaptive_Memory"},{"title":"Dynamic Cheatsheet: Test-Time Learning with Adaptive Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.07952v1"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about Dynamic Cheatsheet and its accuracy improvement results:\n\n## Overview\n\nDynamic Cheatsheet is a lightweight framework that equips language models with persistent, adaptive memory for test-time learning by curating problem-solving strategies. The framework uses a dual-module system—with Generator and Curator modules—and integrates retrieval synthesis to efficiently update its external memory during inference.\n\n## Key Accuracy Improvement Results\n\nThe research demonstrates significant improvements across multiple task categories:\n\n**Math and Reasoning Tasks:**\n- Claude 3.5 Sonnet's accuracy more than doubled on AIME math exams once it began retaining algebraic insights across questions.\n- GPT-4o's success rate on the Game of 24 puzzle increased from about 10% to 99% after the model discovered and reused a Python-based solution.\n- Claude 3.5 Sonnet's accuracy more than doubles in Math Equation Solver, reaching 98%.\n\n**Arithmetic Tasks:**\n- In tasks prone to arithmetic mistakes, such as balancing equations, DC enabled GPT-40 and Claude to reach near-perfect accuracy by recalling previously validated code, whereas their baselines stagnated around 50%.\n\n**Knowledge-Demanding Tasks:**\n- Claude achieved a 9% improvement in GPQA-Diamond and an 8% boost on MMLU-Pro Engineering and Physics problems.\n\n## Key Advantages\n\nDC significantly boosts accuracy on arithmetic, reasoning, and code tasks by enabling cumulative learning without modifying model parameters."],"durationSeconds":11.254928542000242,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"a589ce0b-2c72-4859-99bd-5b80e84ef416","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"e657d1a3-4628-45db-bc7f-b0e21a54bbad","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_018UmxB2omhDMNpnMcYXhvSh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have strong evidence across all three layers. Let me do two more targeted searches to round out the distillation-cost-locally angle and a controlled study on ICL generalization vs fine-tuning."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":505,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1616,"cache_read_input_tokens":24139,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1616,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqRd5w52kW8M4BtfM3B","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"bee5526b-96f9-4871-ad38-56d1008c3e9f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:25.649Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"bee5526b-96f9-4871-ad38-56d1008c3e9f","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_018UmxB2omhDMNpnMcYXhvSh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01D3gjRBfBhp3AKmUHMQu47r","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://pytorch.org/blog/llama-into-torchtune/","prompt":"Extract concrete numbers on the cost and effort of distilling a small model locally (Llama 8B into 1B in torchtune). What hardware was used, how long did training take, what accuracy gains over baseline, and any notes on whether distillation beats plain fine-tuning?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":505,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1616,"cache_read_input_tokens":24139,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1616,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqRd5w52kW8M4BtfM3B","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"a84c9270-f057-4bde-b96f-f34d6125b7e3","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:27.534Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"a84c9270-f057-4bde-b96f-f34d6125b7e3","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_018UmxB2omhDMNpnMcYXhvSh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01QhKk45AxS931kmLJfNGEbn","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.00661v1","prompt":"Extract concrete findings on generalization from in-context learning vs fine-tuning in this controlled study. Which generalizes better, and does combining them (in-context examples augmenting fine-tuning data) help? Any specific numbers."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":505,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1616,"cache_read_input_tokens":24139,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1616,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqRd5w52kW8M4BtfM3B","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"3460c337-f545-44bf-a8ae-ac68aceea1fa","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:28.821Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"a84c9270-f057-4bde-b96f-f34d6125b7e3","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01D3gjRBfBhp3AKmUHMQu47r","type":"tool_result","content":"# Knowledge Distillation Costs and Results: Llama 8B to 1B\n\n## Hardware Used\n- **Single A100 80GB GPU** for the case study\n\n## Training Time\nThe document does not specify training duration or computational cost (wall-clock time, token throughput, etc.).\n\n## Accuracy Gains Over Baseline\n\nUsing the **fine-tuned 8B teacher + baseline 1B student** configuration:\n\n| Dataset | Metric | Baseline 1B | KD Result | Gain |\n|---------|--------|------------|-----------|------|\n| TruthfulQA | mc2 | 0.4384 | 0.4481 | +0.97% |\n| TruthfulQA | acc | 0.4517 | 0.4603 | +1.90% |\n| HellaSwag | acc_norm | 0.6064 | 0.6157 | +1.53% |\n| CommonSense QA | acc | 0.5536 | 0.5569 | +0.60% |\n\n## Distillation vs. Fine-Tuning\n\n**KD outperforms SFT alone:**\n\n| Model | Method | TruthfulQA (mc2) |\n|-------|--------|-----------------|\n| Llama 1.1B | SFT | 22.1 |\n| Llama 1.1B | KD | **22.2** |\n\nThe document notes that \"knowledge distillation methods can outperform supervised fine-tuning (SFT) alone\" based on research literature, though improvements are modest for the 1B scale.\n\n## Key Finding\n\n**Fine-tuning the teacher first improves KD performance.** The authors recommend LoRA fine-tuning the 8B teacher on the target dataset before distillation, as teacher distributions should align with the transfer dataset."}]},"uuid":"6a5719b1-859f-42a3-bc91-33dc636f735d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:34.950Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":191967,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Knowledge Distillation Costs and Results: Llama 8B to 1B\n\n## Hardware Used\n- **Single A100 80GB GPU** for the case study\n\n## Training Time\nThe document does not specify training duration or computational cost (wall-clock time, token throughput, etc.).\n\n## Accuracy Gains Over Baseline\n\nUsing the **fine-tuned 8B teacher + baseline 1B student** configuration:\n\n| Dataset | Metric | Baseline 1B | KD Result | Gain |\n|---------|--------|------------|-----------|------|\n| TruthfulQA | mc2 | 0.4384 | 0.4481 | +0.97% |\n| TruthfulQA | acc | 0.4517 | 0.4603 | +1.90% |\n| HellaSwag | acc_norm | 0.6064 | 0.6157 | +1.53% |\n| CommonSense QA | acc | 0.5536 | 0.5569 | +0.60% |\n\n## Distillation vs. Fine-Tuning\n\n**KD outperforms SFT alone:**\n\n| Model | Method | TruthfulQA (mc2) |\n|-------|--------|-----------------|\n| Llama 1.1B | SFT | 22.1 |\n| Llama 1.1B | KD | **22.2** |\n\nThe document notes that \"knowledge distillation methods can outperform supervised fine-tuning (SFT) alone\" based on research literature, though improvements are modest for the 1B scale.\n\n## Key Finding\n\n**Fine-tuning the teacher first improves KD performance.** The authors recommend LoRA fine-tuning the 8B teacher on the target dataset before distillation, as teacher distributions should align with the transfer dataset.","durationMs":7202,"url":"https://pytorch.org/blog/llama-into-torchtune/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"a84c9270-f057-4bde-b96f-f34d6125b7e3","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"3460c337-f545-44bf-a8ae-ac68aceea1fa","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QhKk45AxS931kmLJfNGEbn","type":"tool_result","content":"# Key Findings on Generalization: In-Context Learning vs Fine-tuning\n\n## Primary Result\nIn-context learning (ICL) consistently outperforms standard fine-tuning across multiple datasets. The researchers state: \"in-context learning can generalize more flexibly than fine-tuning\" when evaluated on systematic holdouts like reversals and syllogistic inferences.\n\n## Specific Performance Data\n\n**Reversal Curse Dataset:**\n- ICL achieved near-ceiling performance on reversals\n- Standard fine-tuning had \"near zero accuracy\"\n- Fine-tuning with augmented data matched ICL's high performance\n\n**Simple Reversals (Nonsense Words):**\n- ICL showed weaker but still noticeable advantages over fine-tuning\n- Augmented fine-tuning improved performance substantially\n\n**Semantic Structure Benchmark:**\n- ICL moderately outperformed standard fine-tuning across splits\n- Fine-tuning generalization to reversals improved when integrated into a broader knowledge structure\n- Augmented fine-tuning often exceeded even ICL performance on original data\n\n## Combining Both Approaches\n\nThe critical innovation: using ICL to generate synthetic training examples that augment fine-tuning datasets dramatically improved results. As the authors note, \"dataset augmentations can bridge the gap to yield improved generalization from fine-tuning,\" sometimes surpassing ICL alone on original datasets.\n\nThis approach leverages ICL's superior generalization capabilities to create richer training signals for fine-tuning."}]},"uuid":"b749c028-a423-4ba0-a913-907601661b8f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:35.469Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":242682,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Key Findings on Generalization: In-Context Learning vs Fine-tuning\n\n## Primary Result\nIn-context learning (ICL) consistently outperforms standard fine-tuning across multiple datasets. The researchers state: \"in-context learning can generalize more flexibly than fine-tuning\" when evaluated on systematic holdouts like reversals and syllogistic inferences.\n\n## Specific Performance Data\n\n**Reversal Curse Dataset:**\n- ICL achieved near-ceiling performance on reversals\n- Standard fine-tuning had \"near zero accuracy\"\n- Fine-tuning with augmented data matched ICL's high performance\n\n**Simple Reversals (Nonsense Words):**\n- ICL showed weaker but still noticeable advantages over fine-tuning\n- Augmented fine-tuning improved performance substantially\n\n**Semantic Structure Benchmark:**\n- ICL moderately outperformed standard fine-tuning across splits\n- Fine-tuning generalization to reversals improved when integrated into a broader knowledge structure\n- Augmented fine-tuning often exceeded even ICL performance on original data\n\n## Combining Both Approaches\n\nThe critical innovation: using ICL to generate synthetic training examples that augment fine-tuning datasets dramatically improved results. As the authors note, \"dataset augmentations can bridge the gap to yield improved generalization from fine-tuning,\" sometimes surpassing ICL alone on original datasets.\n\nThis approach leverages ICL's superior generalization capabilities to create richer training signals for fine-tuning.","durationMs":6457,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.00661v1"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"3460c337-f545-44bf-a8ae-ac68aceea1fa","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b749c028-a423-4ba0-a913-907601661b8f","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01EJm6s6ZCrRg4Rsx8Rgqy49","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive evidence across all three layers. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n## Findings: Relative leverage of self-improvement layers for a local 8B build\n\n### Layer (a) — Skills / experiential memory (in-context, test-time learning)\n\n**Highest gain per unit of engineering, and the gains are large and immediate. No weight updates, no GPU, no training loop.**\n\n- **Dynamic Cheatsheet (test-time learning with adaptive memory, no weight changes):** GPT-4o on Game-of-24 went from ~10% → 99% by discovering and *reusing* a validated Python solution; arithmetic/equation-balancing tasks went from ~50% baseline to near-perfect by recalling previously-validated code; Claude 3.5 Sonnet roughly *doubled* AIME accuracy and gained +9% on GPQA-Diamond and +8% on MMLU-Pro Engineering/Physics — purely by curating reusable strategies in an external memory. This is the single best demonstration that a *retrieve-and-reuse skill/memory layer* compounds without touching weights. Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.07952 (peer-reviewed, EACL 2026: https://aclanthology.org/2026.eacl-long.333/). Reliability: high (published, multiple models, large effect sizes — though the headline numbers are on frontier models, not 8B specifically).\n- **Controlled study (in-context vs fine-tuning generalization):** ICL \"generalizes more flexibly than fine-tuning\" — on the reversal-curse holdout, ICL hit near-ceiling while standard fine-tuning was near-zero. Key compounding insight: use ICL to *generate augmented training data* that later feeds fine-tuning, which then matches or beats ICL. Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2505.00661v1. Reliability: high (controlled experiments).\n- **Self-improving-agent line (Reflexion, Voyager, ExpeL):** agents learn from past failures by appending reflections / storing skills-as-code in a vector DB and retrieving at test time — \"essentially in-context learning,\" no weight updates. A critical caveat: retrieval generalizes only by *similarity to stored cases*, whereas weight-based memory generalizes by abstract rule to unseen inputs — so memory has a ceiling that distillation eventually breaks through. Sources: https://arxiv.org/html/2510.13220, https://arxiv.org/html/2604.27707. Reliability: medium-high (established methods + one critical-perspective paper).\n\n**Caveat for small models:** ICL is weaker on small models. The fair-comparison study (125M–30B) found ICL and fine-tuning \"generalize similarly\" with large variance, and that an 8B-class model is *not* an efficient in-context learner — fine-tuning can beat ICL on some tasks at this size. So for an 8B local build, the skills/memory layer still wins on *engineering-cost-per-gain*, but its raw ceiling is lower than it would be on a frontier model. Sources: https://aclanthology.org/2023.findings-acl.779/ (arXiv https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.16938). Reliability: high.\n\n### Layer (b) — Routing / cascade / navigator\n\n**Strong, well-quantified leverage — but it's primarily a cost/quality lever, and its value depends on having ≥2 capability tiers to route between.** For a single-model local build the \"model cascade\" framing partly degenerates (you only have qwen3:8b + Claude-Code-as-teacher), but the *navigator* idea — picking which sub-policy/context/skill to load — maps directly onto the memory layer above.\n\n- **RouteLLM:** maintain ~95% of frontier quality while routing ~85% of queries to cheaper models → 45–85% cost reduction. On GSM8K, 95% of GPT-4 performance using GPT-4 for only 14% of queries. Sources: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.18665, https://tianpan.co/blog/2025-11-03-llm-routing-model-cascades. Reliability: high (primary paper) / medium (blog synthesis).\n- **FrugalGPT (cascade):** cost-ordered chain with a cheap DistilBERT correctness-classifier that escalates only when confidence is low. Caveat: cascades add latency from multiple sequential calls; pure routing (single call) does not. Source: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.18665 and the cascade survey https://arxiv.org/pdf/2410.10347v3. Reliability: high.\n- **Recommended engineering order (from practitioner synthesis):** semantic caching → intent routing → confidence cascading → fallback chains; production frameworks (LiteLLM, RouteLLM, vLLM semantic router) cut custom dev. One early-abstention result: −13% cost and −5% error for +4.1% abstention. Source: https://tianpan.co/blog/2025-11-03-llm-routing-model-cascades. Reliability: medium.\n\n### Layer (c) — Distillation (fine-tuning a small student on traces)\n\n**Highest ceiling and the only layer that improves the *weights* (generalizes to unseen inputs), but the highest engineering + compute cost and the smallest gain-per-effort — wire it last.**\n\n- **Distilling Llama-3.1 8B → 1B (torchtune, single A100 80GB):** KD beat the baseline student by only ~+1–2% (HellaSwag +1.5%, TruthfulQA-acc +1.9%) and barely edged plain SFT (22.2 vs 22.1 on TruthfulQA-mc2). Crucially: **fine-tune the teacher on the target data *before* distilling.** Source: https://pytorch.org/blog/llama-into-torchtune/. Reliability: high (official PyTorch, exact numbers) — note gains are modest at the 1B scale and require a real GPU, not a 16GB Mac.\n- **Narrow-domain distillation closes the gap:** general benchmarks leave an 8B student ~3–8 pts below a 70B teacher, but on the *specific task you distilled for*, the gap often drops to <2%. 7B students distilled from 33k DeepSeek-R1 traces (Table-R1-SFT) show large in-domain and OOD accuracy gains. Sources: https://www.spheron.network/blog/model-distillation-gpu-cloud-7b-student-70b-teacher/ (vendor blog, treat as indicative), https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.20946. Reliability: medium (vendor) / high (paper).\n- **Prompt-opt + fine-tuning together beats either alone:** optimizing prompts and weights jointly beat weights-only by up to **65%** and prompts-only by up to ~5% on multi-hop QA / math / classification across Mistral-7B, Llama-2-7B, Llama-3-8B. Best ordering was *prompt → fine-tune → prompt* (no single universal winner). This is direct 7–8B evidence that the layers are **complementary, not substitutes** — and that you should have the prompt/skill layer working *before* you fine-tune. Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2407.10930v1. Reliability: high (controlled, 7–8B models).\n\n### Framing layer — Compound AI systems (Berkeley / DSPy)\n\n- **Berkeley BAIR:** system design beats scaling for ROI — their canonical example: tripling training budget moves coding-contest solve-rate 30%→35%, but a *system* that samples-and-filters moves it 30%→80%. AlphaCode 2 (sample 1M, filter), Medprompt (retrieval + ensemble, beats specialized medical models), Gemini CoT@32 (90.04% MMLU vs GPT-4's 86.4%). Key line: \"iterating on a system design is often much faster than waiting for training runs.\" Source: https://bair.berkeley.edu/blog/2024/02/18/compound-ai-systems/. Reliability: high (authoritative, widely cited).\n- **DSPy:** automated prompt/pipeline optimization (MIPROv2) gives measurable lift with no weight changes, far cheaper than fine-tuning; recommended path is few-shot → MIPROv2 → fine-tune only if drift/traffic demands. Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2412.15298v1 and the joint-optimization paper above. Reliability: high.\n\n---\n\n## Ordering recommendation for a local 8B build (qwen3:8b, 16GB)\n\n1. **Skills / experiential memory FIRST (a).** Best gain-per-engineering-hour, no GPU, no training, runs entirely within the 16GB budget (memory is just embedding + retrieval via nomic-embed-text). The Dynamic Cheatsheet / Reflexion / ExpeL evidence shows large compounding gains from retrieve-and-reuse, and it generates the *traces* that layers (b) and (c) later consume. This is also the only layer with zero inference-budget risk.\n\n2. **Navigator / routing SECOND (b).** Cheap to add once memory exists — the navigator decides *which skill/context/sub-policy* to load (this is the form routing takes when you have one local model + a frontier teacher rather than a cost-ordered model fleet). Quantified 45–85% cost wins, and confidence-based escalation to the Claude-Code teacher tier is your natural cascade. Mostly classifier/threshold engineering, no training.\n\n3. **Distillation LAST (c).** Highest ceiling and the only weight-level generalization (breaks the similarity-retrieval ceiling of memory), but highest cost: it needs a real GPU (the torchtune case used an A100; 8B fine-tuning won't fit comfortably in 16GB unified memory — this matches the project's M3 note to \"pick a student small enough\"), and gains-per-effort are smallest. Critically, the 7–8B evidence says distillation pays off most (a) on narrow domains, (b) after the teacher is fine-tuned on the target data, and (c) *after* the prompt/skill layer is already optimized (prompt→fine-tune→prompt). So memory and routing aren't just earlier — they make distillation work better when you do reach it.\n\n**One load-bearing caveat for the 8B size specifically:** ICL/memory is a weaker learner at 8B than at frontier scale, so the memory layer's ceiling is lower than the headline frontier-model numbers suggest — but it remains the correct first move because every later layer (routing data, distillation traces, augmented fine-tuning sets) is bootstrapped from it."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2046,"cache_read_input_tokens":25755,"output_tokens":3585,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2046},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":323,"output_tokens":3585,"cache_read_input_tokens":25755,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2046,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2046,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqSZSw2C25QUwqusPrg","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"552921d7-614a-4001-8669-a3538e1c5a20","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:16:26.921Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
